SIMPLE: fag
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fag
<hw>Fag</hw> <pr>(f⟦acr⟧g)</pr> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A knot or
coarse part in cloth; a flaw.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A cigarette.</def> <mark>[slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A fag end in a cloth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A drudge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>fag</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: fag
<hw>fag</hw> <pr>(f⟦acr⟧g)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A male homosexual;
-- always used disparagingly and considered offensive. Shortened form of
<er>faggot</er>.</def> <mark>[Slang, disparaging.]</mark> ⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> faggot.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fag</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fag
<hw>Fag</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fagged</conjf> <pr>(f⟦acr⟧gd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fagging</conjf> <pr>(f⟦acr⟧g"g⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf.
LG. <ets>fakk</ets> wearied, weary, <ets>vaak</ets> slumber, drowsiness,
OFries. <ets>fai</ets>, equiv. to <ets>f⟦amac⟧ch</ets> devoted to death,
OS. <ets>f⟦emac⟧gi</ets>, OHG. <ets>feigi</ets>, G. <ets>feig</ets>,
<ets>feige</ets>, cowardly, Icel. <ets>feigr</ets> fated to die, AS.
<ets>f⟦aemac⟧ge</ets>, Scot. <ets>faik</ets>, to fail, stop, lower the
price; or perh. the same word as E. <ets>flag</ets> to droop.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To become weary; to tire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Creighton withheld his force till the Italian began to
<qex>fag</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>G. Mackenzie.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To labor to wearness; to work hard; to
drudge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Read, <qex>fag</qex>, and subdue this chapter.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To act as a fag, or perform menial services or
drudgery, for another, as in some English schools.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To fag out</b></col>, <cd>to become untwisted or frayed,
as the end of a rope, or the edge of canvas.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fag</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fag
<hw>Fag</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To tire by labor; to
exhaust; <as>as, he was almost <ex>fagged</ex> out</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything that fatigues.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is such a <qex>fag</qex>, I came back tired to death.</q>
<rj><qau>Miss Austen.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Brain fag</b></col>. <fld>(Med.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Cerebropathy</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fagaceae</ent>⟦br⟧
